            "body": "For reference, see https://github.com/neovim/neovim/pull/27447#issuecomment-1942890548 (and comments above it).\r\n\r\n> > My use case for this would be searching for referenced of a symbol in my buffer that I'm not moused over, so the position could change every time I want to call the handler.\r\n> \r\n> Placing the cursor programmatically works there.\r\n> \r\n> > I'd also like to be able to navigate to the definition of something that isn't under my cursor without polluting the jumplist.\r\n> \r\n> `:help cursor()` says \"Does not change the jumplist.\"\r\n> \r\n> In general I agree that APIs should always take a position (#25509) instead of inspecting the cursor, but these `vim.lsp.buf` APIs are mostly for \"interactive\" tasks (e.g. `rename()` moves the cursor), so the use-case is weaker if it can't be done in a maintainable way.\r\n\r\n",
